The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Thursday, January 22, 2004  The City Diary
																																																		The Board of Secondary Education on Wednesday announced that it would take care of the cost of further studies of visually challenged student Rinku Das, a resident of Ashoknagar, on the northern fringes of the city, who scored 566 in Madhyamik 2003. Rinku met chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee at Writers Buildings on Wednesday afternoon. Bhattacharjee gave away a cheque for Rs 10,000 to Rinku. Board president Dibeyendu Hota said apart from bearing the cost of Rinkus education, the board would supply her with textbooks. The government is also making arrangements to have Rinkus eye tested by reputed opthalmologists.																																																		A gang of miscreants raided a petrol pump in Bataitola, in the Shibpur police station area, Howrah, early on Wednesday morning, and looted Rs 80,000 after forcing open the drawer at the cash counter. According to police, the robbers entered the shop after breaking open a window and beating up an employee who was asleep inside. Police suspect the involvement of a local gang, but no one has been arrested yet. 																																																		The foundation stone of the second phase of the housing complex to be named after Indias cricket skipper Sourav Ganguly  Sourav Abasan  will be laid in Salt Lake on January 28 in the presence of the cricketers wife Dona. Urban development minister Asok Bhattacharya said on Wednesday that the project would be carried out by CMDA. There will be 146 flats of sizes ranging from 1,000 square feet to 1,300 square feet. The flats will come up at FB, CL, AG and AJ blocks of Salt Lake.																																																		The student wing of Trinamul Congress, the Chhatra Parishad, organised a law-violation programme in Phears Lane on Wednesday, which resulted in the arrest of 78 persons, including four women. The Parishad took out a procession from Calcutta University, through BB Ganguly Street, to Phears Lane, protesting against the politicisation and commercialisation of education by the Left Front government. They were also demanding adequate arrangements for admission of students. The procession converged in Phears Lane at around 2.30 pm. In a separate incident, six Parishad supporters were arrested for shouting slogans in front of the main gate of Writers Buildings, at around 2.10 pm. All the arrested persons were taken to Alipore Central jail.																																																		Calcutta-based industrialist Radhey Shyam Goenka, joint chairman of the Emami group of companies, has been appointed honorary consul-general of Poland in the city. The newly-set up consulate at 18, RN Mukherjee Road will be open from Monday to Friday, from 9 am to 4 pm, and will be the representative of Poland in Bengal, Orissa, Jharkhand, Bihar and Sikkim. It will be responsible for economic promotion and delivery of information for Indian organisations wanting to work with Polish firms, organising cultural events and popularising tourism to Poland.																																																		Power supply will be temporarily disrupted in Titagarh, Barrackpore and adjoining areas on January 24, from 11.30 am to 1.30 pm, as the CESC will carry out maintenance of its switch-gears.																																																		Parties supporting and opposing the bus strike clashed at Kadapara, on Narkeldanga Main Road, at 9 am on Wednesday, damaging a private car in the process. Though no injuries were reported, the officer-in-charge of Phoolbagan police station rushed to the spot with a team to prevent further damage.																																																		Haringhata police arrested three persons on Wednesday from an office in Bali, Howrah, on charges of fraud. According to police, Arun Mukherjee, Sujit Mukherjee and Pabitra Pal promised to help subscribers get a loan at a low interest rate, and cheated them in the process. To Ramakrishna Mission Seva